      "date": "2025-10-30 15:20:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI attempted to fix the build errors present in this patch and succeeded. Yay! Now, keep in mind I barely have any idea what I am doing, so please doublecheck the changes I made to make sure they make sense.\n\nThis service is only provided in hopes to be useful and reduce latency from push to getting actual results in the face of trivial code errors\n\nHere's summary of my changes:\nPerfect! The fix is correct. The code now shows proper C syntax:\n\n1. **Before the fix**: The file contained invalid Python syntax (`def python_in_c_wont_compile():` and `return`) which was causing the C compiler to fail parsing the entire file.\n\n2. **After the fix**: The invalid Python code has been completely removed, and the file now contains only valid C code with proper includes, preprocessor directives, variable declarations, and function definitions.\n\n## Summary\n\n**What the fix was:**\nI removed the invalid Python function definition that was introduced by the patch:\n```python\ndef python_in_c_wont_compile():\n  return\n```\n\n**Rationale:**\nThe compilation error occurred because Python syntax was inserted into a C source file. The C compiler couldn't parse the `def` keyword (which is not valid in C), causing it to misinterpret the entire rest of the file as function parameters rather than proper C code. This led to hundreds of cascading syntax errors.\n\nBy removing the Python code, the file now contains only valid C syntax, allowing it to compile successfully. The fix maintains the original C code structure while eliminating the syntax error that was preventing compilation.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
